<TITLE> Nigeria aims for naira convertibility in 2009 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ABUJA, Aug 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Nigerian central bank will eliminate all restrictions on current account transfers and make its naira fully convertible by Jan. 1 2009, Governor Chukwuma Soludo said on Tuesday. The bank will gradually phase out its foreign exchange auctions in favour of interbank dealing, and distribute some fiscal oil revenues to states in dollars to deepen its foreign exchange market, Soludo told a gathering of press, government officials and diplomats. "As the market deepens, the central bank will gradually withdraw from the weekly Dutch auction system and only intervene in the market as may be required to achieve defined policy objectives," Soludo said. Africa's top oil exporter will also redenominate the naira from August 1 next year, removing two zeros, so that 100 old naira will become 1 new naira, he said. Before the announcement, the naira appreciated on the interbank market by 0.58 percent to 126.26 to the dollar, from 127.00 on Monday, in anticipation of the new policy. Nigerian banks sold dollars on fears that the central bank would announce a major revaluation of the naira, traders said. Soludo said the central bank was conscious of the risk of "undue appreciation" of the naira and would do everything to avoid that. But he declined to comment on whether the bank would manage the rate using a band or specific target rate under the new poli
